<dl id="n53097l"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n53" href="#n53097l">N53 (VI.B.46)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n53all.htm#n53097l"> 97(l)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> flare, <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n53097l"><li>FW 344.24 </li><li><a href="../../flex/md/lexmd.htm#n53097l">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/md/l39md.htm#n53097l">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n53097l">MS BL 47480-82v</ms> </li><li>JJA 55:156 <a name="mdd5" href="../../FF/fdra/mda.htm#mdd5">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/md/mdd5.htm#n53097l">Draft: II.3&sect;4.5</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">&ldquo;Get back your own way,&rdquo; he whispered; &ldquo;we&apos;ve bumped into a big patrol. Don&apos;t fire.&rdquo; And as he spoke, with a slight hiss a flare shot up into the night. <p>Now had it not been for that one untimely <mark>flare</mark> this story would never have been written. Indecent curiosity in other wanderers&apos; doings in No Man&apos;s Land is an unprofitable amusement; while the sound of strafing, to say nothing of revolver shots, is calculated to produce a tornado of fire from all directions, administered impartially by friend and foe alike.</p> <small> H.C. McNeile (&ldquo;Sapper&rdquo;) <a name="SJW" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#SJW"><cite title="source">John Walters</cite></a> (1927) A point of Detail, 39-41</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: [Army slang] Flare: a torch used to illuminate positions in its glare. </mm> </dd></dl>
